x4freetext: Thin targets: Commercial Mylar foils (C10xO4xH8)
served as targets and were always chosen to be
thinner than 100 keV.
Thick targets: An oxygen target, about 2 MeV thick.
conventional scintillation counter (NaI)
spectroscopy. The pulse-height resolution of the
NaI(Tl) scintillation counters used was better than or
close to 2% for 15-MeV protons.
At one energy (17.0 MeV) several spectra
were taken with a 1-mm-thick gold surface barrier (Si)
detector (Molechem, Inc.) which was mounted at an
angle of 60.0 degr. with respect to the proton
trajectories. A thick-target survey for elastic
excitation functions was made for 13<Ep<18.5 MeV at
the angles 80, 100, 120, 140, 160 degr. in lab.system.
The absolute cross section normalization for each
thick - target run (covering a range of about 1.5 MeV)
was obtained by comparison to thin-target data for
the corresponding interval. All thick-target cross
sections so obtained are included in elastic cross
sections, thick-target cross sections are given only
for energies where no thin-target data were taken.

x4freetext: Random uncertainties in the differential
cross sections are due to:
* counting statistics,
* the need for background (or C12) subtraction,
* counting loss corrections,
* imperfect reproducibility of energy settings,
* uncertainties in counter geometry and in charge
and angular readings.
ERR-1 wasn`t included in DATA-ERR
systematic errors due to possible faults
in target uniformity, charge integration, and
zero-angle calibration. Systematic cross-section
errors are believed to be smaller than 5% at 15. degr.
and smaller than 3% for all other angles.

energy resolution of 60 keV.
